The original regex `\w+:` matches one or more word characters followed by a colon (like `http:`, `https:`, `ftp:`).
The mutated regex `\w:` matches exactly one word character followed by a colon.

This means the mutation affects how URLs with multi-character protocols are handled. With the original code, a URL like `http://example.com` would match `\w+:` (because `http` is multiple word chars + colon), so the condition `!/^\.*\/|^(?!localhost)\w+:/.test(currentUrlStr)` would be `false`, and the `http://` prefix would NOT be prepended.

With the mutated code, `http://example.com` would NOT match `\w:` (since `http` is more than one char), so the condition would be `true`, and the code would try to prepend `http://` to an already-absolute URL.

